    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(center)">
                <placeName>No. 46 South St.</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">
                <placeName>New York</placeName>
                <date>July 10th 1867</date>
            </p>
            <p>My Dear <addressee>Mr. Leeser</addressee></p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">I have received nothing<lb/> yet from you this month. What is
                the<lb/> matter? I hope you are not sick.<lb/> Since I last wrote you we have been
                in<lb/> much confusion at the office caused by<lb/> a fire on the promises on the
                morning<lb/> of the <date>14th May</date>, causing however, more<lb/> damage by
                water than by fire and obliging<lb/> us to remove to other quarters for a
                month.<lb/> We are now in order again at the <hi rend="underline">old place</hi>.<lb/>
                <persName>E J King</persName> has paid his bill say $18 and<lb/> said he had ordered
                the Occident dis-<lb/>continued. I have not noticed the<lb/>
                <persName>Messr Hendricks</persName> in your printed ackno<lb/>wledgements. I
                enclose copy of a noti<lb/> recd from <persName>Mr. Morrison</persName> a few days
                since<lb/> for your guidance in mailing.</p>
            <p>Tomorrow I start on an excursion to</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p><placeName>Trenton</placeName> &amp; <placeName>Niagara Falls</placeName>,
                    <placeName>Montreal</placeName><lb/>
                <placeName>Quebec</placeName> &amp; c &amp; c contemplating an absence<lb/> of about
                2 weeks. I go not so much<lb/> for my own pleasure as I do to gratify<lb/> a friend
                enfeebled by long sickness,<lb/> in the hope that he may be
                <sic>benefitted</sic>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I was very glad to hear something from<lb/> you regarding
                    <persName>Dr Wolff</persName> and family, as<lb/> it was the first I had heard
                from<lb/> or of them since I left <placeName>Mobile</placeName> always<lb/> remember
                me most kindly when wri<lb/>ting to them. I fear they have a very<lb/> hard time of
                it under <add>?</add>
                <persName>Stevens</persName><lb/> Military rule. What a pity
                        <persName>Sam<add>?</add></persName> made<lb/> such a mistake as to trust
                everything to<lb/> the Confederates.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">With affectionate remembrance to <persName>Mr.<lb/>
                    Cozens</persName> and <persName>Ella</persName> and best wishes for<lb/> their
                health and happiness as well as<lb/> your own.</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">I remain in great haste</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">sincerely yours</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">
                <persName role="author">H S. Hanford</persName>
            </p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Copy</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">
                <placeName>No. 3. Charles St.</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(2)"><date>July 2 1867</date>.</p>
            <p><persName>Mrs. Morrison</persName> regrets not having<lb/> answered <persName>Mrs.
                    Hanford's</persName> note before<lb/>
                <persName>Mr. <sic>Morrisons</sic></persName> ill health has pre<lb/>vented her.
                Will thank him to<lb/> stop the Occident until their<lb/> return from the country
                when<lb/> they will discharge the amount<lb/> owing.</p>
        </body>
